## Engineering Principles (Mandatory)

All code must follow SOLID, DRY, OOP, and DDP. See `flutter-architecture` skill for details.

Key rules:
- No `dynamic` in production code (only at I/O boundaries, converted to typed models immediately)
- No magic numbers / hard-coded strings — use constants, theme, `flutter_screenutil`, and localization
- No business logic in widget `build()` methods
- No direct package imports in domain layer — zero exceptions
- Every external package wrapped behind a helper interface

---

## Approval Gates

Require explicit user approval BEFORE:

- Adding or upgrading any package in `pubspec.yaml`
- Modifying files in `android/`, `ios/`, `.github/workflows/`, or CI configs
- Running `git commit`, `git push`, or any remote-mutating git operation
- Running destructive commands (`rm`, mass file moves, `git reset --hard`)
- Changes spanning more than 3 files — show the plan first
- Refactoring the public API of any feature

Routine work (tests, single-file analyzer fixes, `*.g.dart` regeneration) — proceed without asking.

---

## Required Workflow After Code Changes

In order. Report results before declaring done:

1. `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs` — if annotations changed
2. `flutter analyze` — zero errors/warnings
3. `flutter test` — all tests pass

Failures must be fixed before continuing.

